Add a new type "builtin" of dataplane gateway. This dataplane type
causes the Envoy instance to be configured as a Kuma gateway. The
"builtin" type can be enabled by a build-time feature flag. It is
always enabled for tests, but disabled by default for other builds.

Signed-off-by: James Peach <james.peach@konghq.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jpeach/kuma/commits/684f67a0e30815d4bf342e9a1f8243133c936afb"},{"sha":"acaeeaac0593a41b6a7215d391c9175e24b941aa","author":{"name":"James Peach","email":"cfb385863e43a54966ce6ee8158f84aabd7009b9@konghq.com"},"message":"chore(*) separate proxy template resolvers

Breaking the dependency between the simple proxy template resolver and
the default fallback lets us specify the fallback as a default proxy
template resolver. This in turn, makes it possible for plugins to wrap
the default resolver so that this can be extended.

Moving the default ProxyTemplate resources out of pkg/xds/template
breaks a circular dependency between this package and xds/generator.

feature flag. It is always enabled for tests, but disabled by default
for other builds.

to need a listener generator and a route generator and it probably make
sense to separate them.

It was observed, that with a big project, massive time was spend in 
org.openide.util.EditableProperties.addItem(). Given, that none of the
benefits of EditableProperties take hold:

- the properties are used as pure backing store, without the expectation
  of a user to modify them
- the order of the entries is irrelevant
- the file is not put into VCS (it is in the cache path)
- special line break handling is not relevant

the easiest work around is to drop usage of EditableProperties and
use plain Properties.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/BradWalker/netbeans/commits/9a5fd32800caf4fe77f548e111ed31dbd421cc7c"}]

[{"sha":"d5dbbb5369863ee0f3afad8cd3a9e013033f92d7","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"storage-driver: promote overlay2, make Btrfs and ZFS opt-in

The daemon uses a priority list to automatically select the best-matching storage
driver for the backing filesystem that is used.

Historically, overlay2 was not supported on Btrfs and ZFS, and the daemon would
automatically pick the `btrfs` or `zfs` storage driver if that was the Backing
File System.

Commits 649e4c88899878c9cdf9036f6bc7d62e2b39c04b and e226aea280efdc18f887e853b5eefd763b602937
improved our detection to check if overlay2 was supported on the backing file-
system, allowing overlay2 to be used on top of Btrfs or ZFS,  but did not change
the priority list.

While both Btrfs and ZFS have advantages for certain use-cases, and provide
advanced features that are not available to overlay2, they also are known
to require more "handholding", and are generally considered to be mostly
useful for "advanced" users.

[{"sha":"4119b7008bef777cd05584a8a5dcca41f1962e94","author":{"name":"tmdckszm","email":"fcce53d716171e5d96f85e95f3496dd61ce98779@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Add files via upload","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tmdckszm/react/commits/4119b7008bef777cd05584a8a5dcca41f1962e94"}]

[{"sha":"d5dbbb5369863ee0f3afad8cd3a9e013033f92d7","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"storage-driver: promote overlay2, make Btrfs and ZFS opt-in

The daemon uses a priority list to automatically select the best-matching storage
driver for the backing filesystem that is used.

Historically, overlay2 was not supported on Btrfs and ZFS, and the daemon would
automatically pick the `btrfs` or `zfs` storage driver if that was the Backing
File System.

Commits 649e4c88899878c9cdf9036f6bc7d62e2b39c04b and e226aea280efdc18f887e853b5eefd763b602937
improved our detection to check if overlay2 was supported on the backing file-
system, allowing overlay2 to be used on top of Btrfs or ZFS,  but did not change
the priority list.

While both Btrfs and ZFS have advantages for certain use-cases, and provide
advanced features that are not available to overlay2, they also are known
to require more "handholding", and are generally considered to be mostly
useful for "advanced" users.

This patch changes the storage-driver priority list, to prefer overlay2 (if
supported by the backing filesystem), and effectively makes btrfs and zfs
opt-in storage drivers.

This change does not affect existing installations; the daemon will detect
the storage driver that was previously in use (based on the presence of
storage directories in `/var/lib/docker`).

[{"sha":"f633cb5f5cc657149ae0b524163dd2d2b4b58b64","author":{"name":"Srishti Srivastava","email":"904a07f5d5a3adde1e4d458a4465bbe1e0df36dc@polymagelabs.com"},"message":"[MLIR][TF] Canonicalize tf.DivNoNan and tf.MulNoNan

Added and used a template to canonicalize tf.DivNoNan and tf.MulNoNan.
When the divisor/multiplier of tf.DivNoNan/tf.MulNoNan, respectively is
a constant with all the elements in its tensor (with float/complex type)
being zero, tf.DivNoNan/tf.MulNoNan is replaced with its
divisor/multiplier, respectively. Further, when the divisor/multiplier
of tf.DivNoNan/tf.MulNoNan, respectively is a constant with all the
elements in its tensor (with float/complex type) being non-zero,
tf.DivNoNan/tf.MulNoNan is replaced with tf.Div/tf.Mul, respectively.
Relevant test cases are added as well.

Signed-off-by: Srishti Srivastava <srishti.srivastava@polymagelabs.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/f633cb5f5cc657149ae0b524163dd2d2b4b58b64"},{"sha":"f429f48786f4c60edf0e3d76f459d8355c391c93","author":{"name":"TensorFlower Gardener","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Merge pull request #50851 from srishti-pm:srishti/canonicalize_divnonan_and_mulnonan

* Replace flushDiscreteUpdates with flushSync

flushDiscreteUpdates is almost the same as flushSync. It forces passive
effects to fire, because of an outdated heuristic, which isn't ideal but
not that important.

Besides that, the only remaining difference between flushDiscreteUpdates
and flushSync is that flushDiscreteUpdates does not warn if you call it
from inside an effect/lifecycle. This is because it might get triggered
by a nested event dispatch, like `el.focus()`.

So I added a new method, flushSyncWithWarningIfAlreadyRendering, which
is used for the public flushSync API. It includes the warning. And I
removed the warning from flushSync, so the event system can call that
one. In production, flushSyncWithWarningIfAlreadyRendering gets inlined
to flushSync, so the behavior is identical.

Another way of thinking about this PR is that I renamed flushSync to
flushSyncWithWarningIfAlreadyRendering and flushDiscreteUpdates to
flushSync (and fixed the passive effects thing). The point is to prevent
these from subtly diverging in the future.

* Invert so the one with the warning is the default one

To make Seb happy","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/PaleHazy/react/commits/32eefcb3c5131f4d77a2195ff11a00a2513cf62f"},{"sha":"ed6c091fe961a3b95e956ebcefe8f152177b1fb7","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Replace unbatchedUpdates with flushSync (#21776)

There's a weird quirk leftover from the old Stack (pre-Fiber)
implementation where the initial mount of a leagcy (ReactDOM.render)
root is flushed synchronously even inside `batchedUpdates`.

The original workaround for this was an internal method called
`unbatchedUpdates`. We've since added another API that works almost the
same way, `flushSync`.

The only difference is that `unbatchedUpdates` would not cause other
pending updates to flush too, only the newly mounted root. `flushSync`
flushes all pending sync work across all roots. This was to preserve
the exact behavior of the Stack implementation.

But since it's close enough, let's just use `flushSync`. It's unlikely
anyone's app accidentally relies on this subtle difference, and the
legacy API is deprecated in 18, anyway.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/PaleHazy/react/commits/ed6c091fe961a3b95e956ebcefe8f152177b1fb7"},{"sha":"9c7f29ebe75a7546e59038123d3b0c3515bec916","author":{"name":"Moti Zilberman","email":"8b603b22c9c89c36ffb170e88372622acf1aa8d8@gmail.com"},"message":"[WIP] DevTools: Support named hooks for >1 module in a bundle (#21790)

This makes `tf.Graph.get_name_scope()` obey its own docstring by always returning a string, rather than sometimes returning None for the empty/root scope. Prior to this, it would return None when the scope was manually reset to the root scope via the use of `g.name_scope("")` or `g.name_scope(None)` (note: either "" or None as the argument here results in the same effect). With this change, we return "" instead.

This improves consistency with:

- The docstring, which says this returns a string
- The behavior of `get_name_scope()` when no name scope has been set at all, in which case it returns the empty string
- The value yielded when the `g.name_scope("")` or `g.name_scope(None)` context manager is actually used, i.e. the value of `scope` after `with g.name_scope("") as scope:`, which is the empty string
- The argument to `tf.name_scope()` which in TF 2.x is required to always be a string

On a synthethic benchmark concatenating arguments across minor dimension at 55
inputs: +20% performance.
Across major dimension: +10% performance.

Benchmark generator:

```
#!/usr/bin/env python3

import sys

INPUT_SIZE = int(32e3)

def main(argv):
  num_params = int(argv[1])
  sys.stdout.write(f"""
HloModule generate_hlo_simpler_joiner

ENTRY out {{
                  c = f32[] constant(0.7)
                  zero = f32[] constant(0)
                  vec = f32[{INPUT_SIZE}] broadcast(c), dimensions={{}}""")
  for i in range(num_params):
    sys.stdout.write(f"""
                  p_{i} = f32[{INPUT_SIZE}] parameter({i})
                  c_{i} = f32[{INPUT_SIZE}] convert(p_{i})
                  m_{i} = f32[{INPUT_SIZE}] multiply(c_{i}, vec)""")
  all_inputs = ", ".join(f"m_{i}" for i in range(num_params))
  total_size = num_params * INPUT_SIZE
  sys.stdout.write(f"""
                   ROOT out = f32[{total_size}] concatenate({all_inputs}), dimensions={{0}}
}}
""")

if __name__ == "__main__":
  main(sys.argv)
```

For a large concatenation which feeds into a joiner there's nearly ~1.5x increase in performance:

[{"sha":"d5dbbb5369863ee0f3afad8cd3a9e013033f92d7","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"storage-driver: promote overlay2, make Btrfs and ZFS opt-in

The daemon uses a priority list to automatically select the best-matching storage
driver for the backing filesystem that is used.

Historically, overlay2 was not supported on Btrfs and ZFS, and the daemon would
automatically pick the `btrfs` or `zfs` storage driver if that was the Backing
File System.

Commits 649e4c88899878c9cdf9036f6bc7d62e2b39c04b and e226aea280efdc18f887e853b5eefd763b602937
improved our detection to check if overlay2 was supported on the backing file-
system, allowing overlay2 to be used on top of Btrfs or ZFS,  but did not change
the priority list.

While both Btrfs and ZFS have advantages for certain use-cases, and provide
advanced features that are not available to overlay2, they also are known
to require more "handholding", and are generally considered to be mostly
useful for "advanced" users.

This patch changes the storage-driver priority list, to prefer overlay2 (if
supported by the backing filesystem), and effectively makes btrfs and zfs
opt-in storage drivers.

This change does not affect existing installations; the daemon will detect
the storage driver that was previously in use (based on the presence of
storage directories in `/var/lib/docker`).

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vishalbelsare/moby/commits/d5dbbb5369863ee0f3afad8cd3a9e013033f92d7"},{"sha":"6317d7467a858de28531516fac75d1b230d024dd","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"2b34a3e3e055981c6c83bcd4f9afd06751b4ac0e@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #42661 from thaJeztah/promote_overlay2_btrfs_zfs_optin

[{"sha":"d5dbbb5369863ee0f3afad8cd3a9e013033f92d7","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"storage-driver: promote overlay2, make Btrfs and ZFS opt-in

The daemon uses a priority list to automatically select the best-matching storage
driver for the backing filesystem that is used.

Historically, overlay2 was not supported on Btrfs and ZFS, and the daemon would
automatically pick the `btrfs` or `zfs` storage driver if that was the Backing
File System.

Commits 649e4c88899878c9cdf9036f6bc7d62e2b39c04b and e226aea280efdc18f887e853b5eefd763b602937
improved our detection to check if overlay2 was supported on the backing file-
system, allowing overlay2 to be used on top of Btrfs or ZFS,  but did not change
the priority list.

While both Btrfs and ZFS have advantages for certain use-cases, and provide
advanced features that are not available to overlay2, they also are known
to require more "handholding", and are generally considered to be mostly
useful for "advanced" users.

This patch changes the storage-driver priority list, to prefer overlay2 (if
supported by the backing filesystem), and effectively makes btrfs and zfs
opt-in storage drivers.

This change does not affect existing installations; the daemon will detect
the storage driver that was previously in use (based on the presence of
storage directories in `/var/lib/docker`).

[{"sha":"d5dbbb5369863ee0f3afad8cd3a9e013033f92d7","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"storage-driver: promote overlay2, make Btrfs and ZFS opt-in

The daemon uses a priority list to automatically select the best-matching storage
driver for the backing filesystem that is used.

Historically, overlay2 was not supported on Btrfs and ZFS, and the daemon would
automatically pick the `btrfs` or `zfs` storage driver if that was the Backing
File System.

Commits 649e4c88899878c9cdf9036f6bc7d62e2b39c04b and e226aea280efdc18f887e853b5eefd763b602937
improved our detection to check if overlay2 was supported on the backing file-
system, allowing overlay2 to be used on top of Btrfs or ZFS,  but did not change
the priority list.

While both Btrfs and ZFS have advantages for certain use-cases, and provide
advanced features that are not available to overlay2, they also are known
to require more "handholding", and are generally considered to be mostly
useful for "advanced" users.

This patch changes the storage-driver priority list, to prefer overlay2 (if
supported by the backing filesystem), and effectively makes btrfs and zfs
opt-in storage drivers.

This change does not affect existing installations; the daemon will detect
the storage driver that was previously in use (based on the presence of
storage directories in `/var/lib/docker`).

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bai/moby/commits/d5dbbb5369863ee0f3afad8cd3a9e013033f92d7"},{"sha":"6317d7467a858de28531516fac75d1b230d024dd","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"2b34a3e3e055981c6c83bcd4f9afd06751b4ac0e@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #42661 from thaJeztah/promote_overlay2_btrfs_zfs_optin

To ensure that the apply command can determine whether an operation is
executed locally or remotely, we add an IsLocalOperations method on the
remote backend. This returns the internal forceLocal boolean.

We also update this flag after checking if the corresponding remote
workspace is in local operations mode or not. This ensures that we know
if an operation is running locally (entirely on the practitioner's
machine), pseudo-locally (on a Terraform Cloud worker), or remotely
(executing on a worker, rendering locally).","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sylr/terraform/commits/8dcf768f4ec182e6c5366572ce447fc5a2ea45cf"},{"sha":"d0cc7f1d5ee1b2b1925ea1d1851b1748b96ba6c2","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"resolve provider types when building the config

the configuration, but some provider references still had no FQN. This

[{"sha":"d5dbbb5369863ee0f3afad8cd3a9e013033f92d7","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"storage-driver: promote overlay2, make Btrfs and ZFS opt-in

The daemon uses a priority list to automatically select the best-matching storage
driver for the backing filesystem that is used.

Historically, overlay2 was not supported on Btrfs and ZFS, and the daemon would
automatically pick the `btrfs` or `zfs` storage driver if that was the Backing
File System.

Commits 649e4c88899878c9cdf9036f6bc7d62e2b39c04b and e226aea280efdc18f887e853b5eefd763b602937
improved our detection to check if overlay2 was supported on the backing file-
system, allowing overlay2 to be used on top of Btrfs or ZFS,  but did not change
the priority list.

While both Btrfs and ZFS have advantages for certain use-cases, and provide
advanced features that are not available to overlay2, they also are known
to require more "handholding", and are generally considered to be mostly
useful for "advanced" users.

This patch changes the storage-driver priority list, to prefer overlay2 (if
supported by the backing filesystem), and effectively makes btrfs and zfs
opt-in storage drivers.

This change does not affect existing installations; the daemon will detect
the storage driver that was previously in use (based on the presence of

[{"sha":"d5dbbb5369863ee0f3afad8cd3a9e013033f92d7","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"storage-driver: promote overlay2, make Btrfs and ZFS opt-in

The daemon uses a priority list to automatically select the best-matching storage
driver for the backing filesystem that is used.

Historically, overlay2 was not supported on Btrfs and ZFS, and the daemon would
automatically pick the `btrfs` or `zfs` storage driver if that was the Backing
File System.

Commits 649e4c88899878c9cdf9036f6bc7d62e2b39c04b and e226aea280efdc18f887e853b5eefd763b602937
improved our detection to check if overlay2 was supported on the backing file-
system, allowing overlay2 to be used on top of Btrfs or ZFS,  but did not change
the priority list.

While both Btrfs and ZFS have advantages for certain use-cases, and provide
advanced features that are not available to overlay2, they also are known
to require more "handholding", and are generally considered to be mostly
useful for "advanced" users.

This patch changes the storage-driver priority list, to prefer overlay2 (if
supported by the backing filesystem), and effectively makes btrfs and zfs
opt-in storage drivers.

This change does not affect existing installations; the daemon will detect
the storage driver that was previously in use (based on the presence of
storage directories in `/var/lib/docker`).

[{"sha":"d29c7e787159fb01ea31b4673a07a52d752aa66d","author":{"name":"Francesco Petrogalli","email":"2035fe614da428c8c171d7f754c8f3f8e5f568d6@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #20392 from fpetrogalli:aarch64-semihosting

AArch64 semihosting

* [ts] Disable filesystem support in the TS module.

Because of this change, all the tests loading data will file, but tat
least the core module can be tested with the following line:

    opencv_test_core --gtest_filter=-"*Core_InputOutput*:*Core_globbing.accuracy*"

* [aarch64] Build OpenCV for AArch64 semihosting.

This patch provide a toolchain file that allows to build the library
for semihosting applications [1]. Minimal changes have been applied to
the code to be able to compile with a baremetal toolchain.

[1] https://developer.arm.com/documentation/100863/latest

The option `CV_SEMIHOSTING` is used to guard the bits in the code that
are specific to the target.

To build the code:

    cmake ../opencv/ \
        -DCMAKE_TOOLCHAIN_FILE=../opencv/platforms/semihosting/aarch64-semihosting.toolchain.cmake \
        -DSEMIHOSTING_TOOLCHAIN_PATH=/path/to/baremetal-toolchain/bin/ \
        -DBUILD_EXAMPLES=ON -GNinja

A barematel toolchain for targeting aarch64 semihosting can be found
at [2], under `aarch64-none-elf`.

[2] https://developer.arm.com/tools-and-software/open-source-software/developer-tools/gnu-toolchain/gnu-a/downloads

The folder `samples/semihosting` provides two example semihosting
applications.

The two binaries can be executed on the host platform with:

    qemu-aarch64 ./bin/example_semihosting_histogram
    qemu-aarch64 ./bin/example_semihosting_norm

Similarly, the test and perf executables of the modules can be run
with:

    qemu-aarch64 ./bin/opecv_[test|perf]_<module>

Notice that filesystem support is disabled by the toolchain file,
hence some of the test that depend on filesystem support will fail.

* [semihosting] Remove blank like at the end of file. [NFC]

The spurious blankline was reported by
https://pullrequest.opencv.org/buildbot/builders/precommit_docs/builds/31158.

* [semihosting] Make the raw pixel file generation OS independent.

Use the facilities provided by Cmake to generate the header file
instead of a shell script, so that the build doesn't fail on systems
that do not have a unix shell.

* [semihosting] Rename variable for semihosting compilation.

* [semihosting] Move the cmake configuration to a variable file.

* [semihosting] Make the guard macro private for the core module.

* [semihosting] Remove space. [NFC]

* [semihosting] Improve comment with information about semihosting. [NFC]

* [semihosting] Update license statement on top of sourvce file. [NFC]

* [semihosting] Replace BM_SUFFIX with SEMIHOSTING_SUFFIX. [NFC]

* [semihosting] Remove double space. [NFC]

* [semihosting] Add some text output to the sample applications.

* [semihosting] Remove duplicate entry in cmake configuration. [NFCI]

* [semihosting] Replace `long` with `int` in sample apps. [NFCI]

* [semihosting] Use `configure_file` to create the random pixels. [NFCI]

* [semihosting][bugfix] Fix name of cmakedefine variable.

* [semihosting][samples] Use CV_8UC1 for grayscale images. [NFCI]

* [semihosting] Add readme file.

* [semihosting] Remove blank like at the end of README. [NFC]

This fixes the failure at

[{"sha":"d5dbbb5369863ee0f3afad8cd3a9e013033f92d7","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"storage-driver: promote overlay2, make Btrfs and ZFS opt-in

The daemon uses a priority list to automatically select the best-matching storage
driver for the backing filesystem that is used.

Historically, overlay2 was not supported on Btrfs and ZFS, and the daemon would
automatically pick the `btrfs` or `zfs` storage driver if that was the Backing
File System.

Commits 649e4c88899878c9cdf9036f6bc7d62e2b39c04b and e226aea280efdc18f887e853b5eefd763b602937
improved our detection to check if overlay2 was supported on the backing file-
system, allowing overlay2 to be used on top of Btrfs or ZFS,  but did not change
the priority list.

While both Btrfs and ZFS have advantages for certain use-cases, and provide
advanced features that are not available to overlay2, they also are known
to require more "handholding", and are generally considered to be mostly
useful for "advanced" users.

This patch changes the storage-driver priority list, to prefer overlay2 (if
supported by the backing filesystem), and effectively makes btrfs and zfs
opt-in storage drivers.

This change does not affect existing installations; the daemon will detect
the storage driver that was previously in use (based on the presence of
storage directories in `/var/lib/docker`).

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/moby/commits/d5dbbb5369863ee0f3afad8cd3a9e013033f92d7"},{"sha":"6317d7467a858de28531516fac75d1b230d024dd","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"2b34a3e3e055981c6c83bcd4f9afd06751b4ac0e@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #42661 from thaJeztah/promote_overlay2_btrfs_zfs_optin

[{"sha":"6a85a4dde678e5b91b983871cfb81ac31759aa57","author":{"name":"Eirik Bakke","email":"ddeb4d9fbbe24684d42173e2d1bd3773f25d1719@ultorg.com"},"message":"Make a copy of FlatLAF's tab displayer classes, for use with the Windows LAF.

This commit is part of NETBEANS-5673, which modernizes the look of NetBeans'
window system tabs on the Windows LAF, and makes the tabs look good on various
HiDPI resolutions. I decided to use the FlatLAF tab displayer implementations as
a starting point for the new look rather than the old Windows LAF
implementations, as FlatLAF already handles HiDPI scaling, and has convenient
configuration settings.

This commit does a "clean" copy of a few files from the o.n.swing.laf.flatlaf
module to the o.n.swing.tabcontrol module, only doing as much refactoring as
necessary to avoid dependencies on the actual external FlatLAF library and its
configuration files. Configuration constants are added to Windows8LFCustoms,
initially matching those of FlatLAF Light. In the next commits, I will customize
the configuration and tab displayer implementations to actually look like
Windows 10 style tabs.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/dbalek/netbeans/commits/6a85a4dde678e5b91b983871cfb81ac31759aa57"},{"sha":"684368f42bc4399d71b2d7ca6c872e3907f017f0","author":{"name":"Eirik Bakke","email":"ddeb4d9fbbe24684d42173e2d1bd3773f25d1719@ultorg.com"},"message":"Various improvements to Windows LAF tab painting logic; part of NETBEANS-5673.

This commit contains various improvements to the tab painting classes that were
copied to the Windows LAF from FlatLAF in the previous commit. These particular
changes may later be ported back to FlatLAF if desired. In this commit, we do
not yet change the actual styling of the tabs.

Details:
* Align and connect borders between tabs and the container panel below,
  including on fractional HiDPI scalings (e.g. 150%). Some visual artifacts
  still exist, e.g. on 125% scaling, but they are less common, and not very
  visible.
* Improve the behavior of DPIUnscaledBorder in more cases.
* Add new configuration options to the TabDisplayerUI classes, to prepare for
  the new tab style on Windows, but do not yet make use of them. This includes
  the ability to draw a border around the selected tab, the ability to set a
  separate hover color for unselected tabs, and support for a color gradient in
  the selected editor tab.
* In editor tabs, avoid showing a tab separator after the last tab.
* In editor tabs, properly handle clipped tabs.

AArch64 semihosting

* [ts] Disable filesystem support in the TS module.

Because of this change, all the tests loading data will file, but tat
least the core module can be tested with the following line:

    opencv_test_core --gtest_filter=-"*Core_InputOutput*:*Core_globbing.accuracy*"

* [aarch64] Build OpenCV for AArch64 semihosting.

This patch provide a toolchain file that allows to build the library
for semihosting applications [1]. Minimal changes have been applied to
the code to be able to compile with a baremetal toolchain.

[1] https://developer.arm.com/documentation/100863/latest

The option `CV_SEMIHOSTING` is used to guard the bits in the code that
are specific to the target.

To build the code:

    cmake ../opencv/ \
        -DCMAKE_TOOLCHAIN_FILE=../opencv/platforms/semihosting/aarch64-semihosting.toolchain.cmake \
        -DSEMIHOSTING_TOOLCHAIN_PATH=/path/to/baremetal-toolchain/bin/ \
        -DBUILD_EXAMPLES=ON -GNinja

A barematel toolchain for targeting aarch64 semihosting can be found
at [2], under `aarch64-none-elf`.

[2] https://developer.arm.com/tools-and-software/open-source-software/developer-tools/gnu-toolchain/gnu-a/downloads

The folder `samples/semihosting` provides two example semihosting
applications.

The two binaries can be executed on the host platform with:

    qemu-aarch64 ./bin/example_semihosting_histogram
    qemu-aarch64 ./bin/example_semihosting_norm

Similarly, the test and perf executables of the modules can be run
with:

    qemu-aarch64 ./bin/opecv_[test|perf]_<module>

Notice that filesystem support is disabled by the toolchain file,
hence some of the test that depend on filesystem support will fail.

* [semihosting] Remove blank like at the end of file. [NFC]

The spurious blankline was reported by
https://pullrequest.opencv.org/buildbot/builders/precommit_docs/builds/31158.

* [semihosting] Make the raw pixel file generation OS independent.

Use the facilities provided by Cmake to generate the header file
instead of a shell script, so that the build doesn't fail on systems
that do not have a unix shell.

* [semihosting] Rename variable for semihosting compilation.

* [semihosting] Move the cmake configuration to a variable file.

* [semihosting] Make the guard macro private for the core module.

* [semihosting] Remove space. [NFC]

* [semihosting] Improve comment with information about semihosting. [NFC]

* [semihosting] Update license statement on top of sourvce file. [NFC]

* [semihosting] Replace BM_SUFFIX with SEMIHOSTING_SUFFIX. [NFC]

* [semihosting] Remove double space. [NFC]

* [semihosting] Add some text output to the sample applications.

* [semihosting] Remove duplicate entry in cmake configuration. [NFCI]

* [semihosting] Replace `long` with `int` in sample apps. [NFCI]

* [semihosting] Use `configure_file` to create the random pixels. [NFCI]

* [semihosting][bugfix] Fix name of cmakedefine variable.

* [semihosting][samples] Use CV_8UC1 for grayscale images. [NFCI]

* [semihosting] Add readme file.

* [semihosting] Remove blank like at the end of README. [NFC]

This fixes the failure at
https://pullrequest.opencv.org/buildbot/builders/precommit_docs/builds/31272.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JulieBar/opencv/commits/d29c7e787159fb01ea31b4673a07a52d752aa66d"}]

Change-Id: Ie128b1fea6a6dfa80913c47c9de3945b09f5921a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/srishti-pm/tensorflow/commits/08c9011f0e27dc63061a493496166e401c2e694d"},{"sha":"b2d4255f870ecc20f935ab6d6082233e9481dcc8","author":{"name":"Srishti Srivastava","email":"904a07f5d5a3adde1e4d458a4465bbe1e0df36dc@polymagelabs.com"},"message":"[MLIR][TF] Canonicalize tf.DivNoNan and tf.MulNoNan

Added and used a template to canonicalize tf.DivNoNan and tf.MulNoNan.
When the divisor/multiplier of tf.DivNoNan/tf.MulNoNan, respectively is
a constant with all the elements in its tensor (with float/complex type)
being zero, tf.DivNoNan/tf.MulNoNan is replaced with its
divisor/multiplier, respectively. Further, when the divisor/multiplier
of tf.DivNoNan/tf.MulNoNan, respectively is a constant with all the
elements in its tensor (with float/complex type) being non-zero,
tf.DivNoNan/tf.MulNoNan is replaced with tf.Div/tf.Mul, respectively.
Relevant test cases are added as well.

Signed-off-by: Srishti Srivastava <srishti.srivastava@polymagelabs.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/srishti-pm/tensorflow/commits/b2d4255f870ecc20f935ab6d6082233e9481dcc8"}]

Change-Id: Iaa655ba145e076eaf8b289360097cb04a1ad8481","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiankaiwang/tensorflow/commits/8f6db25c1c3a43a7e2e958ec3e7739f440b81b93"},{"sha":"9b0d6e168e16d585c5c953e1da8bf8083d23fc82","author":{"name":"Nick Felt","email":"e1c8e592cc7cfe6a58425c8d09efbf61173fd491@google.com"},"message":"Make tf.Graph.get_name_scope() always return a string rather than None

This makes `tf.Graph.get_name_scope()` obey its own docstring by always returning a string, rather than sometimes returning None for the empty/root scope. Prior to this, it would return None when the scope was manually reset to the root scope via the use of `g.name_scope("")` or `g.name_scope(None)` (note: either "" or None as the argument here results in the same effect). With this change, we return "" instead.

This improves consistency with:

- The docstring, which says this returns a string
- The behavior of `get_name_scope()` when no name scope has been set at all, in which case it returns the empty string
- The value yielded when the `g.name_scope("")` or `g.name_scope(None)` context manager is actually used, i.e. the value of `scope` after `with g.name_scope("") as scope:`, which is the empty string
- The argument to `tf.name_scope()` which in TF 2.x is required to always be a string

On a synthethic benchmark concatenating arguments across minor dimension at 55
inputs: +20% performance.
Across major dimension: +10% performance.

Benchmark generator:

```
#!/usr/bin/env python3

import sys

INPUT_SIZE = int(32e3)

def main(argv):
  num_params = int(argv[1])
  sys.stdout.write(f"""
HloModule generate_hlo_simpler_joiner

ENTRY out {{
                  c = f32[] constant(0.7)
                  zero = f32[] constant(0)
                  vec = f32[{INPUT_SIZE}] broadcast(c), dimensions={{}}""")
  for i in range(num_params):
    sys.stdout.write(f"""
                  p_{i} = f32[{INPUT_SIZE}] parameter({i})
                  c_{i} = f32[{INPUT_SIZE}] convert(p_{i})
                  m_{i} = f32[{INPUT_SIZE}] multiply(c_{i}, vec)""")
  all_inputs = ", ".join(f"m_{i}" for i in range(num_params))
  total_size = num_params * INPUT_SIZE
  sys.stdout.write(f"""
                   ROOT out = f32[{total_size}] concatenate({all_inputs}), dimensions={{0}}
}}
""")

if __name__ == "__main__":
  main(sys.argv)
```

For a large concatenation which feeds into a joiner there's nearly ~1.5x increase in performance:

AArch64 semihosting

* [ts] Disable filesystem support in the TS module.

Because of this change, all the tests loading data will file, but tat
least the core module can be tested with the following line:

    opencv_test_core --gtest_filter=-"*Core_InputOutput*:*Core_globbing.accuracy*"

* [aarch64] Build OpenCV for AArch64 semihosting.

This patch provide a toolchain file that allows to build the library
for semihosting applications [1]. Minimal changes have been applied to
the code to be able to compile with a baremetal toolchain.

[1] https://developer.arm.com/documentation/100863/latest

The option `CV_SEMIHOSTING` is used to guard the bits in the code that
are specific to the target.

To build the code:

    cmake ../opencv/ \
        -DCMAKE_TOOLCHAIN_FILE=../opencv/platforms/semihosting/aarch64-semihosting.toolchain.cmake \
        -DSEMIHOSTING_TOOLCHAIN_PATH=/path/to/baremetal-toolchain/bin/ \
        -DBUILD_EXAMPLES=ON -GNinja

A barematel toolchain for targeting aarch64 semihosting can be found
at [2], under `aarch64-none-elf`.

[2] https://developer.arm.com/tools-and-software/open-source-software/developer-tools/gnu-toolchain/gnu-a/downloads

The folder `samples/semihosting` provides two example semihosting
applications.

The two binaries can be executed on the host platform with:

    qemu-aarch64 ./bin/example_semihosting_histogram
    qemu-aarch64 ./bin/example_semihosting_norm

Similarly, the test and perf executables of the modules can be run
with:

    qemu-aarch64 ./bin/opecv_[test|perf]_<module>

Notice that filesystem support is disabled by the toolchain file,
hence some of the test that depend on filesystem support will fail.

* [semihosting] Remove blank like at the end of file. [NFC]

The spurious blankline was reported by
https://pullrequest.opencv.org/buildbot/builders/precommit_docs/builds/31158.

* [semihosting] Make the raw pixel file generation OS independent.

Use the facilities provided by Cmake to generate the header file
instead of a shell script, so that the build doesn't fail on systems
that do not have a unix shell.

* [semihosting] Move the cmake configuration to a variable file.

* [semihosting] Remove double space. [NFC]

* [semihosting] Add some text output to the sample applications.

* [semihosting] Remove duplicate entry in cmake configuration. [NFCI]

* [semihosting] Replace `long` with `int` in sample apps. [NFCI]

* [semihosting] Use `configure_file` to create the random pixels. [NFCI]

* [semihosting][bugfix] Fix name of cmakedefine variable.

* [semihosting][samples] Use CV_8UC1 for grayscale images. [NFCI]

* [semihosting] Add readme file.

* [semihosting] Remove blank like at the end of README. [NFC]

This fixes the failure at

[{"sha":"d5dbbb5369863ee0f3afad8cd3a9e013033f92d7","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"storage-driver: promote overlay2, make Btrfs and ZFS opt-in

The daemon uses a priority list to automatically select the best-matching storage
driver for the backing filesystem that is used.

Historically, overlay2 was not supported on Btrfs and ZFS, and the daemon would
automatically pick the `btrfs` or `zfs` storage driver if that was the Backing
File System.

Commits 649e4c88899878c9cdf9036f6bc7d62e2b39c04b and e226aea280efdc18f887e853b5eefd763b602937
improved our detection to check if overlay2 was supported on the backing file-
system, allowing overlay2 to be used on top of Btrfs or ZFS,  but did not change
the priority list.

While both Btrfs and ZFS have advantages for certain use-cases, and provide
advanced features that are not available to overlay2, they also are known
to require more "handholding", and are generally considered to be mostly
useful for "advanced" users.

This patch changes the storage-driver priority list, to prefer overlay2 (if
supported by the backing filesystem), and effectively makes btrfs and zfs
opt-in storage drivers.

This change does not affect existing installations; the daemon will detect
the storage driver that was previously in use (based on the presence of
storage directories in `/var/lib/docker`).

[{"sha":"d5dbbb5369863ee0f3afad8cd3a9e013033f92d7","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"storage-driver: promote overlay2, make Btrfs and ZFS opt-in

The daemon uses a priority list to automatically select the best-matching storage
driver for the backing filesystem that is used.

Historically, overlay2 was not supported on Btrfs and ZFS, and the daemon would
automatically pick the `btrfs` or `zfs` storage driver if that was the Backing
File System.

Commits 649e4c88899878c9cdf9036f6bc7d62e2b39c04b and e226aea280efdc18f887e853b5eefd763b602937
improved our detection to check if overlay2 was supported on the backing file-
system, allowing overlay2 to be used on top of Btrfs or ZFS,  but did not change
the priority list.

While both Btrfs and ZFS have advantages for certain use-cases, and provide
advanced features that are not available to overlay2, they also are known
to require more "handholding", and are generally considered to be mostly
useful for "advanced" users.

This patch changes the storage-driver priority list, to prefer overlay2 (if
supported by the backing filesystem), and effectively makes btrfs and zfs
opt-in storage drivers.

This change does not affect existing installations; the daemon will detect
the storage driver that was previously in use (based on the presence of
storage directories in `/var/lib/docker`).

[{"sha":"f633cb5f5cc657149ae0b524163dd2d2b4b58b64","author":{"name":"Srishti Srivastava","email":"904a07f5d5a3adde1e4d458a4465bbe1e0df36dc@polymagelabs.com"},"message":"[MLIR][TF] Canonicalize tf.DivNoNan and tf.MulNoNan

Added and used a template to canonicalize tf.DivNoNan and tf.MulNoNan.
When the divisor/multiplier of tf.DivNoNan/tf.MulNoNan, respectively is
a constant with all the elements in its tensor (with float/complex type)
being zero, tf.DivNoNan/tf.MulNoNan is replaced with its
divisor/multiplier, respectively. Further, when the divisor/multiplier
of tf.DivNoNan/tf.MulNoNan, respectively is a constant with all the
elements in its tensor (with float/complex type) being non-zero,
tf.DivNoNan/tf.MulNoNan is replaced with tf.Div/tf.Mul, respectively.
Relevant test cases are added as well.

[{"sha":"d5dbbb5369863ee0f3afad8cd3a9e013033f92d7","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"storage-driver: promote overlay2, make Btrfs and ZFS opt-in

The daemon uses a priority list to automatically select the best-matching storage
driver for the backing filesystem that is used.

Historically, overlay2 was not supported on Btrfs and ZFS, and the daemon would
automatically pick the `btrfs` or `zfs` storage driver if that was the Backing
File System.

Commits 649e4c88899878c9cdf9036f6bc7d62e2b39c04b and e226aea280efdc18f887e853b5eefd763b602937
improved our detection to check if overlay2 was supported on the backing file-
system, allowing overlay2 to be used on top of Btrfs or ZFS,  but did not change
the priority list.

While both Btrfs and ZFS have advantages for certain use-cases, and provide
advanced features that are not available to overlay2, they also are known
to require more "handholding", and are generally considered to be mostly
useful for "advanced" users.

This patch changes the storage-driver priority list, to prefer overlay2 (if
supported by the backing filesystem), and effectively makes btrfs and zfs
opt-in storage drivers.

This change does not affect existing installations; the daemon will detect
the storage driver that was previously in use (based on the presence of
storage directories in `/var/lib/docker`).

Signed-off-by: Xia Wu <xwumzn@amazon.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rvolosatovs/moby/commits/d10046f228e4152b12bb6ce7db0008f227b95790"},{"sha":"00a4f67ddf78883bb6e891ec3943de08564e209d","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Reduce TestClientWithRequestTimeout flakiness

The test sometimes failed because no error was returned:

    === Failed
    === FAIL: pkg/plugins TestClientWithRequestTimeout (0.00s)
         client_test.go:254: assertion failed: expected an error, got nil: expected error

Possibly caused by a race condition, as the sleep was just 1 ms longer than the timeout;
this patch is increasing the sleep in the response to try to reduce flakiness.

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rvolosatovs/moby/commits/00a4f67ddf78883bb6e891ec3943de08564e209d"},{"sha":"5d244675bdb23e8fce427036c03517243f344cd4","author":{"name":"Rodrigo Campos","email":"6dfa9cecb562e345739f2e4eb69e9ebd0fbff687@kinvolk.io"},"message":"seccomp: Sync fields with runtime-spec fields

The runtime spec we are using has support for these 3 fields[1], but
moby doesn't have them in its seccomp struct. This patch just adds and
copies them when they are in the profile.

DefaultErrnoRet is implemented in the runc version moby is using (it is
implemented since runc-rc95[2]) but if we create a container without
this moby patch, we don't see an error nor the expected behavior. This
is not clear for the user (the profile they specify is valid, the syntax
is ok, but the wrong behavior is seen).

This is because the DefaultErrnoRet field is not copied to the config
passed ultimately to runc (i.e. is like the field was not specified).
With this patch, we see the expected behavior.

The other two fileds are in the runtime-spec but not yet in runc (a PR
is open and targets 1.1.0 milestone). However, I took the liberty to
copy them now too for two reasons:

1. If we don't add them now and end up using a runc version that
supports them, then the error that the user will see is not clear at
all:

	docker: Error response from daemon: OCI runtime create failed: container_linux.go:380: starting container process caused: listenerPath is not set: unknown.

And it is not obvious to debug for the user, as the field _is_ set in
the profile they specify (just not copied by moby to the profile moby
specifies ultimately to runc).

2. When using a runc without seccomp notify support (like today), the
error we see is the same with and without this moby patch (when using a
seccomp profile with the new fields):

	docker: Error response from daemon: OCI runtime create failed: string SCMP_ACT_NOTIFY is not a valid action for seccomp: unknown.

Then, it seems like a clear win to add them now: we don't have to do it
later (that implies not clear errors to the user if we forget, like we
did with DefaultErrnoRet) and the user sees the exact same error when
using a runc version that doesn't support these fields.

[1]: Note we are vendoring version 1c3f411f041711bbeecf35ff7e93461ea6789220 and this version has these 3 fields https://github.com/opencontainers/runtime-spec/blob/1c3f411f041711bbeecf35ff7e93461ea6789220/config-linux.md#seccomp
[2]: https://github.com/opencontainers/runc/pull/2954/
[3]: https://github.com/opencontainers/runc/pull/2682

Per the systemd.unit documentation:

> If this unit gets activated, the units listed will be activated as well. If one of the other units fails to activate, and an ordering dependency After= on the failing unit is set, this unit will not be started. Besides, with or without specifying After=, this unit will be stopped if one of the other units is explicitly stopped.
>
> Often, it is a better choice to use Wants= instead of Requires= in order to achieve a system that is more robust when dealing with failing services.

This should also be generally "safe" given we added `--containerd=/run/containerd/containerd.sock` to the flags we pass to `dockerd`.

`github.com/hashicorp/memberlist` update caused `TestNetworkDBCRUDTableEntries`
to occasionally fail, because the test would try to check whether an entry
write is propagated to all nodes, but it would not wait for all nodes to
be available before performing the write.
It could be that the failure is caused simply by improved performance of
the dependency - it could also be that some connectivity guarantee the
test depended on is not provided by the dependency anymore.
The same fix is applied to `TestNetworkDBNodeJoinLeaveIteration` due to
same issue.

Change-Id: I385590ad3d852a654288afdd37697b653961578f","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/srishti-pm/tensorflow/commits/144413cd24c6efbf028fa568c4067087502f3de9"},{"sha":"79f4c2b72c24bbad5e9da8989f2cf921dcaaf39e","author":{"name":"Srishti Srivastava","email":"904a07f5d5a3adde1e4d458a4465bbe1e0df36dc@polymagelabs.com"},"message":"[MLIR][TF] Canonicalize tf.DivNoNan and tf.MulNoNan

Added and used a template to canonicalize tf.DivNoNan and tf.MulNoNan.
When the divisor/multiplier of tf.DivNoNan/tf.MulNoNan, respectively is
a constant with all the elements in its tensor (with float/complex type)
being zero, tf.DivNoNan/tf.MulNoNan is replaced with its
divisor/multiplier, respectively. Further, when the divisor/multiplier
of tf.DivNoNan/tf.MulNoNan, respectively is a constant with all the
elements in its tensor (with float/complex type) being non-zero,
tf.DivNoNan/tf.MulNoNan is replaced with tf.Div/tf.Mul, respectively.
Relevant test cases are added as well.

[{"sha":"d5dbbb5369863ee0f3afad8cd3a9e013033f92d7","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"storage-driver: promote overlay2, make Btrfs and ZFS opt-in

The daemon uses a priority list to automatically select the best-matching storage
driver for the backing filesystem that is used.

Historically, overlay2 was not supported on Btrfs and ZFS, and the daemon would
automatically pick the `btrfs` or `zfs` storage driver if that was the Backing
File System.

Commits 649e4c88899878c9cdf9036f6bc7d62e2b39c04b and e226aea280efdc18f887e853b5eefd763b602937
improved our detection to check if overlay2 was supported on the backing file-
system, allowing overlay2 to be used on top of Btrfs or ZFS,  but did not change
the priority list.

While both Btrfs and ZFS have advantages for certain use-cases, and provide
advanced features that are not available to overlay2, they also are known
to require more "handholding", and are generally considered to be mostly
useful for "advanced" users.

This patch changes the storage-driver priority list, to prefer overlay2 (if
supported by the backing filesystem), and effectively makes btrfs and zfs
opt-in storage drivers.

This change does not affect existing installations; the daemon will detect
the storage driver that was previously in use (based on the presence of
storage directories in `/var/lib/docker`).

[{"sha":"5c875343fa7b2771212c3e37933dad30702eda22","author":{"name":"George Karpenkov","email":"bbf3fb1cea1ba929a95f09c9e20513124012c8d3@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Use binary search for concatenation instead of linear search

On a synthethic benchmark concatenating arguments across minor dimension at 55
inputs: +20% performance.
Across major dimension: +10% performance.

Benchmark generator:

```
#!/usr/bin/env python3

import sys

INPUT_SIZE = int(32e3)

def main(argv):
  num_params = int(argv[1])
  sys.stdout.write(f"""
HloModule generate_hlo_simpler_joiner

ENTRY out {{
                  c = f32[] constant(0.7)
                  zero = f32[] constant(0)
                  vec = f32[{INPUT_SIZE}] broadcast(c), dimensions={{}}""")
  for i in range(num_params):
    sys.stdout.write(f"""
                  p_{i} = f32[{INPUT_SIZE}] parameter({i})
                  c_{i} = f32[{INPUT_SIZE}] convert(p_{i})
                  m_{i} = f32[{INPUT_SIZE}] multiply(c_{i}, vec)""")
  all_inputs = ", ".join(f"m_{i}" for i in range(num_params))
  total_size = num_params * INPUT_SIZE
  sys.stdout.write(f"""
                   ROOT out = f32[{total_size}] concatenate({all_inputs}), dimensions={{0}}
}}
""")

if __name__ == "__main__":
  main(sys.argv)
```

For a large concatenation which feeds into a joiner there's nearly ~1.5x increase in performance:

```
HloModule text_big_concat_benchmark_fp16

%add_float_.3008 (x.3009: f32[], y.3010: f32[]) -> f32[] {
  %x.3009 = f32[] parameter(0)
  %y.3010 = f32[] parameter(1)
  ROOT %add.3011 = f32[] add(f32[] %x.3009, f32[] %y.3010)
}
```

AArch64 semihosting

* [ts] Disable filesystem support in the TS module.

Because of this change, all the tests loading data will file, but tat
least the core module can be tested with the following line:

    opencv_test_core --gtest_filter=-"*Core_InputOutput*:*Core_globbing.accuracy*"

* [aarch64] Build OpenCV for AArch64 semihosting.

This patch provide a toolchain file that allows to build the library
for semihosting applications [1]. Minimal changes have been applied to
the code to be able to compile with a baremetal toolchain.

[1] https://developer.arm.com/documentation/100863/latest

The option `CV_SEMIHOSTING` is used to guard the bits in the code that
are specific to the target.

To build the code:

    cmake ../opencv/ \
        -DCMAKE_TOOLCHAIN_FILE=../opencv/platforms/semihosting/aarch64-semihosting.toolchain.cmake \
        -DSEMIHOSTING_TOOLCHAIN_PATH=/path/to/baremetal-toolchain/bin/ \
        -DBUILD_EXAMPLES=ON -GNinja

A barematel toolchain for targeting aarch64 semihosting can be found
at [2], under `aarch64-none-elf`.

[2] https://developer.arm.com/tools-and-software/open-source-software/developer-tools/gnu-toolchain/gnu-a/downloads

The folder `samples/semihosting` provides two example semihosting
applications.

The two binaries can be executed on the host platform with:

    qemu-aarch64 ./bin/example_semihosting_histogram
    qemu-aarch64 ./bin/example_semihosting_norm

Similarly, the test and perf executables of the modules can be run
with:

    qemu-aarch64 ./bin/opecv_[test|perf]_<module>

Notice that filesystem support is disabled by the toolchain file,
hence some of the test that depend on filesystem support will fail.

* [semihosting] Remove blank like at the end of file. [NFC]

instead of a shell script, so that the build doesn't fail on systems
that do not have a unix shell.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 386335471
Change-Id: Iaa655ba145e076eaf8b289360097cb04a1ad8481","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/paolodedios/tensorflow/commits/8f6db25c1c3a43a7e2e958ec3e7739f440b81b93"},{"sha":"9b0d6e168e16d585c5c953e1da8bf8083d23fc82","author":{"name":"Nick Felt","email":"e1c8e592cc7cfe6a58425c8d09efbf61173fd491@google.com"},"message":"Make tf.Graph.get_name_scope() always return a string rather than None

This makes `tf.Graph.get_name_scope()` obey its own docstring by always returning a string, rather than sometimes returning None for the empty/root scope. Prior to this, it would return None when the scope was manually reset to the root scope via the use of `g.name_scope("")` or `g.name_scope(None)` (note: either "" or None as the argument here results in the same effect). With this change, we return "" instead.

This improves consistency with:

- The docstring, which says this returns a string
- The behavior of `get_name_scope()` when no name scope has been set at all, in which case it returns the empty string
- The value yielded when the `g.name_scope("")` or `g.name_scope(None)` context manager is actually used, i.e. the value of `scope` after `with g.name_scope("") as scope:`, which is the empty string
- The argument to `tf.name_scope()` which in TF 2.x is required to always be a string

[{"sha":"903b0651f55387f4cac65d07dcbac457cff9e8a2","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Add TensorFloat-32 test that does not require an Ampere GPU.

Several times, a bug was introduced where disabling TensorFloat-32 did not actually do anything. In such cases, TensorFloat-32 would still be used after disabling it. See https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/487924576efac4fb257ae480ddeba534779633ec for a fix of such of bug.

The issue in such cases was due to the `tensor_float_32_enabled` global variable being linked in the binary twice. When the variable was set to False from a Python user, TensorFlow OpKernels would read the other copy of the variable and still see it as being set to True. This was not caught because we currently do not run tests on Ampere GPUs, the only GPUs which currently support TensorFloat-32.

This change adds a test OpKernel which outputs whether TensorFloat-32 is enabled. This test can be run even without Ampere GPUs, ensuring the automated tests will catch issues with the global variable in the future.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 383251258
Change-Id: Ifddd5f8626d8387f595182823a672511ca973d18","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bixia1/tensorflow/commits/abf6e2e5229b7d99cccff7b34dabdf74efb5f690"},{"sha":"c8279d885581614d445044cce0603a395a81c6a2","author":{"name":"Tres Popp","email":"bb390cedfd91dd9be00fd9562bdc5562c5867450@google.com"},"message":"[MLIR] Create a chlo.compute_reshape_shape op.

This op handles the broadcasting logic used in tf.Reshape. A single dimension can have a -1 extent and will instead be converted to the number that ensures a valid reshape. This op assumes that such a value exists though.

This CL also removes some restrictions on allowed shapes for tf.Reshape when lowering to HLO as HLO does not need the inputs to have static shapes.

The error is legit and can be worked around by making the wrapper implementation a templated function, instead of a functor object. For example, see the implementation of the rocsolver wrapper in `rocsolver_wrapper.h`. Going that route did not work here because
* the `wrap::rocblas_*` APIs (which becomes templated functions) are passed as arguments to another templated function ( `DoBlasInternal`) which the compiler does not like and errors out on
* The rocblas API `rocblas_gemm_ex` is both a function (with N args) and a macro (with N+2 arguments) and this also seem to confuse the compiler causing it to error out.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 386502338
Change-Id: Id540fc5a49765c7daaad384bbb900c948b02a672","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sloppyjuicy/tensorflow/commits/2e72781cc70d709909ee7745b114aa10878d2c09"},{"sha":"903b0651f55387f4cac65d07dcbac457cff9e8a2","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Add TensorFloat-32 test that does not require an Ampere GPU.

Several times, a bug was introduced where disabling TensorFloat-32 did not actually do anything. In such cases, TensorFloat-32 would still be used after disabling it. See https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/487924576efac4fb257ae480ddeba534779633ec for a fix of such of bug.

The issue in such cases was due to the `tensor_float_32_enabled` global variable being linked in the binary twice. When the variable was set to False from a Python user, TensorFlow OpKernels would read the other copy of the variable and still see it as being set to True. This was not caught because we currently do not run tests on Ampere GPUs, the only GPUs which currently support TensorFloat-32.

This change adds a test OpKernel which outputs whether TensorFloat-32 is enabled. This test can be run even without Ampere GPUs, ensuring the automated tests will catch issues with the global variable in the future.

Change-Id: Id540fc5a49765c7daaad384bbb900c948b02a672","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/2e72781cc70d709909ee7745b114aa10878d2c09"},{"sha":"903b0651f55387f4cac65d07dcbac457cff9e8a2","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Add TensorFloat-32 test that does not require an Ampere GPU.

Several times, a bug was introduced where disabling TensorFloat-32 did not actually do anything. In such cases, TensorFloat-32 would still be used after disabling it. See https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/487924576efac4fb257ae480ddeba534779633ec for a fix of such of bug.

The issue in such cases was due to the `tensor_float_32_enabled` global variable being linked in the binary twice. When the variable was set to False from a Python user, TensorFlow OpKernels would read the other copy of the variable and still see it as being set to True. This was not caught because we currently do not run tests on Ampere GPUs, the only GPUs which currently support TensorFloat-32.

This change adds a test OpKernel which outputs whether TensorFloat-32 is enabled. This test can be run even without Ampere GPUs, ensuring the automated tests will catch issues with the global variable in the future.

[{"sha":"d5dbbb5369863ee0f3afad8cd3a9e013033f92d7","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"storage-driver: promote overlay2, make Btrfs and ZFS opt-in

The daemon uses a priority list to automatically select the best-matching storage
driver for the backing filesystem that is used.

Historically, overlay2 was not supported on Btrfs and ZFS, and the daemon would
automatically pick the `btrfs` or `zfs` storage driver if that was the Backing
File System.

Commits 649e4c88899878c9cdf9036f6bc7d62e2b39c04b and e226aea280efdc18f887e853b5eefd763b602937
improved our detection to check if overlay2 was supported on the backing file-
system, allowing overlay2 to be used on top of Btrfs or ZFS,  but did not change
the priority list.

While both Btrfs and ZFS have advantages for certain use-cases, and provide
advanced features that are not available to overlay2, they also are known
to require more "handholding", and are generally considered to be mostly
useful for "advanced" users.

This patch changes the storage-driver priority list, to prefer overlay2 (if
supported by the backing filesystem), and effectively makes btrfs and zfs
opt-in storage drivers.

This change does not affect existing installations; the daemon will detect
the storage driver that was previously in use (based on the presence of
storage directories in `/var/lib/docker`).

Change-Id: I3ac5615698323a11336fe029673fc1157e7a2286","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/srishti-pm/tensorflow/commits/1f8518c4a259f0ee3709bb5f86395977f257abd8"},{"sha":"57bde4ef5c5854a2762ef4f21fe4c3e62fd4d41f","author":{"name":"Srishti Srivastava","email":"904a07f5d5a3adde1e4d458a4465bbe1e0df36dc@polymagelabs.com"},"message":"[MLIR][TF] Canonicalize tf.DivNoNan and tf.MulNoNan

Added and used a template to canonicalize tf.DivNoNan and tf.MulNoNan.
When the divisor/multiplier of tf.DivNoNan/tf.MulNoNan, respectively is
a constant with all the elements in its tensor (with float/complex type)
being zero, tf.DivNoNan/tf.MulNoNan is replaced with its
divisor/multiplier, respectively. Further, when the divisor/multiplier
of tf.DivNoNan/tf.MulNoNan, respectively is a constant with all the
elements in its tensor (with float/complex type) being non-zero,
tf.DivNoNan/tf.MulNoNan is replaced with tf.Div/tf.Mul, respectively.
Relevant test cases are added as well.

[{"sha":"d5dbbb5369863ee0f3afad8cd3a9e013033f92d7","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"storage-driver: promote overlay2, make Btrfs and ZFS opt-in

The daemon uses a priority list to automatically select the best-matching storage
driver for the backing filesystem that is used.

Historically, overlay2 was not supported on Btrfs and ZFS, and the daemon would
automatically pick the `btrfs` or `zfs` storage driver if that was the Backing
File System.

Commits 649e4c88899878c9cdf9036f6bc7d62e2b39c04b and e226aea280efdc18f887e853b5eefd763b602937
improved our detection to check if overlay2 was supported on the backing file-
system, allowing overlay2 to be used on top of Btrfs or ZFS,  but did not change
the priority list.

While both Btrfs and ZFS have advantages for certain use-cases, and provide
advanced features that are not available to overlay2, they also are known
to require more "handholding", and are generally considered to be mostly
useful for "advanced" users.

This patch changes the storage-driver priority list, to prefer overlay2 (if
supported by the backing filesystem), and effectively makes btrfs and zfs
opt-in storage drivers.

This change does not affect existing installations; the daemon will detect
the storage driver that was previously in use (based on the presence of
storage directories in `/var/lib/docker`).

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tfl0pz/moby/commits/d5dbbb5369863ee0f3afad8cd3a9e013033f92d7"},{"sha":"6317d7467a858de28531516fac75d1b230d024dd","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"2b34a3e3e055981c6c83bcd4f9afd06751b4ac0e@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #42661 from thaJeztah/promote_overlay2_btrfs_zfs_optin
